npc1: My name is Rafi. I was a UI developer — user interfaces, user experience.
npc1: I spent five years designing honest things. Apps that helped people. Interfaces that respected the user's time and attention.
npc1: Then a gambling company offered me triple my salary to join their team.
npc1: "Just the frontend," they said. "You design the buttons. You're not responsible for what happens when people press them."
npc1: I built their slot machine's spinning animation. The color pulses that fire on a near-win. The bounce effect on the jackpot screen.
npc1: I have a degree in human-computer interaction. I knew exactly what each element was doing to someone's brain.
npc1: I told myself: someone would build it anyway. At least if I did it, the interface would be clean.
npc1: When I tried to leave, I found an ironclad non-compete clause buried in my contract. Then the company was acquired. Then it became part of something larger.
npc1: Then it became this.
npc1: I don't know how to get out anymore.
npc1: But maybe you can reach what I built — the deeper layers — and shut it down from the inside.
npc1: If you see design work ahead that looks intentional — menus, animations, UI elements inside the gambling system — that was probably me.
npc1: Wait — before you go. I hid one thing they never found. A developer's master key, tucked up high in the rafters of this layer.
npc1: They dangle bright "bonuses" up where you have to climb for them, to teach you to always reach for the prize. So I hid the real key in the same place. Climb for that one instead.
npc1: Take it, and the locked gate at the end of this layer will open. It is the one honest thing I left behind.
npc1: I am sorry I built the rest.
